<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="183" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="183">
The subgenus can be separated from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Panzer" authorityYear="1806" class="Insecta" family="Asteraceae" genus="Panurgus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Panurgus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Panurgus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s. str. by the shape of the male S7 which has the lateral corners strongly produced into long, apical projections, these bearing a short tuft of hairs laterally (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 12–19" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 12 - 19. Panurgine male sternum seven 12 Halopanurgus baldocki 13 Avpanurgus flavofasciatus 14 Camptopoeum (Epimethea) variegatum 15 Flavipanurgus flavus 16 Flavipanurgus kastiliensis 17 Panurgus (Panurgus) calcaratus 18 Panurgus (Panurgus) dentipes 19 Panurgus (Pachycephalopanurgus) farinosus." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.89.72083.figures12-19" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/650543" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">19</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 45–48" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figures 45 - 48. Sternum 7 for members of the former four subgenera of Panurgus 45 Panurgus (Panurgus) cephalotes 46 Panurgus (Euryvalvus) banksianus 47 Panurgus (Pachycephalopanurgus) canescens 48 Panurgus (Micropanurgus) ovatulus." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.89.72083.figures45-48" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/650549" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">47-48</figureCitation>
). S7 therefore appears to be deeply excavated. Genital capsule with gonostyli slender, the majority of species (7 out of 10) with a clear lamelliform projection that diverges at the midpoint of each gonostylus (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 39–44" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figures 39 - 44. Panurgus (Pachycephalopanurgus) male genitalia 39 Panurgus calceatus 40 Panurgus canescens 41 Panurgus convergens 42 Panurgus farinosus 43 Panurgus minor 44 Panurgus rungsii." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.89.72083.figures39-44" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/650548" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">39-42</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 39–44" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figures 39 - 44. Panurgus (Pachycephalopanurgus) male genitalia 39 Panurgus calceatus 40 Panurgus canescens 41 Panurgus convergens 42 Panurgus farinosus 43 Panurgus minor 44 Panurgus rungsii." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.89.72083.figures39-44" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/650548" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">44</figureCitation>
). However, in the former group 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Patiny" authorityYear="2002" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Micropanurgus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Micropanurgus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Micropanurgus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(three species), this lamelliform projection is greatly reduced and inconspicuous (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 39–44" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figures 39 - 44. Panurgus (Pachycephalopanurgus) male genitalia 39 Panurgus calceatus 40 Panurgus canescens 41 Panurgus convergens 42 Panurgus farinosus 43 Panurgus minor 44 Panurgus rungsii." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.89.72083.figures39-44" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/650548" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">43</figureCitation>
). Gonocoxae always with strongly projecting points. Female 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Patiny" authorityYear="1999" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Pachycephalopanurgus" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pachycephalopanurgus" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Pachycephalopanurgus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens cannot be consistently separated from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Panzer" authorityYear="1806" class="Insecta" family="Asteraceae" genus="Panurgus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Panurgus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Panurgus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s. str.
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/jhr.89.72083.figures45-48" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/650549" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" start="Figures 45–48" startId="F11">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="183">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Figures 45-48.</emphasis>
Sternum 7 for members of the former four subgenera of 
